  {title: "Welcome to my Website.", text: "      <p>I am a philosopher, employed currently as \"Oberassistent\" (roughly fixed-term senior research associate / lecturer) at the University of Lucerne (Chair of Philosophy, Faculty of Theology).  I am also an editor of <a href=\"http://dialectica.philosophie.ch\">dialectica</a>, an international philosophy journal, the founder and vice-president of <a href=\"http://www.philosophie.ch/\">www.philosophie.ch</a> and the project manager of ousia, the Swiss Doctoral Program in Philosophy.\r\n\r\n      <p>\r\n\r\n      <p>I am married to <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/rosalia.blum\">Rosalia Blum</a>, and father of two daughters: Aurora (born 2012) and Amalia (born 2014). Some time ago, I have changed my name from \"Keller\" to \"Blum\".\r\n\r\n      <p>Before coming to Lucerne, I spent a year at Humboldt University in Berlin, working on Kant, and before that (and a paternal break) another year working with Logos, at the University of Barcelona.  Even before that, I was a scientific collaborator at the philosophy department of the University of Geneva, coordinator of the research group eidos and a research consultant at the Faculty of Humanities of the University of Lausanne. Even before that,  I spent the academic year 2009-2010 as a postdoctoral researcher at the Universidad Nacional Aut&oacute;noma de M&eacute;xico.\r\n\r\n      <p If you want to contact me, please send me an email to <? email('philipp.blum@philosophie.ch');?>.\r\n\r\n      <p>My CV is available <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"/getpdf/cv\">here</a>.</p>", section: "welcome", url: nil},
  {title: "Workshops", text: "  <p>I am an avid workshop organiser and participant. I believe that informal, constructive and focussed workhops are a very cost-effective means to achieve philosophical progress. Over the years, I have organised XX workshops, eight annual graduate schools, two installments of the \"Geneva Summer School in the Philosophy of Physics\", seven semesters of the Geneva graduate school colloquium, 13 \"sequitur\" workshops and two major international conferences (which each more than 120 speakers and about 200 participants):\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><a href=\"espp07.php\">ESPP 2007 - European Society for Philosophy and Psychology congress</a>, 9th to 12th of July 2007\r\n    <li><a href=\"sopha09.php\">SOPHA09 - congr&egrave;s triannuel de la Soci&eacute;t&eacute; Francophone de Philosophie Analytique</a>, Wednesday 2nd of September to Saturday 5th of September (Geneva)</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <br>\r\n\r\n\r\n  <h2>graduate schools</h2>\r\n  <p>I have been organising the following summer schools in Geneva (4 to 8 workshops each):\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><a href=\"graduateschool13.php\">2013 graduate school in metaphysics</a>\r\n    <li><a href=\"graduateschool12.php\">2012 graduate school in metaphysics</a>\r\n    <li><a href=\"graduateschool11.php\">2011 graduate school in metaphysics</a>\r\n    <li><a href=\"summerschool07.php\">2007 graduate school in metaphysics</a>\r\n    <li><a href=\"summerschool06.php\">2006 graduate school in metaphysics</a>\r\n    <li><a href=\"summerschool04.php\">2004 graduate school in metaphysics</a>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <br>\r\n  <br>\r\n\r\n  <h2>workshops</h2>\r\n  <p>Until now, I have been the sole or responsible organiser for quite a number of workshops and conferences:\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><a href=\"1stmeeting.php\">first eidos meeting</a>, 13th to 14th of July 2007</li>\r\n    <li><a href=\"2ndmeeting.php\">second eidos meeting</a>,11th to 12th of September 2007</li>\r\n    <li><a href=\"launch.php\">eidos launch conference</a> (Carrie Jenkins, Andrew McGonigal, Andreas H&uuml;ttemann, Wolfang Schwarz, Ralph Busse, Michael Esfeld), Thursday 13th to Saturday 15th of September 2007</li>\r\n    <li><a href=\"vectors.php\">the metaphysics of vectors</a> (Dean Zimmerman, John Bigelow, Peter Simons, Stephan Leuenberger, Daniel Nolan, Barry Smith, Ralf Busse, Ingvar Johansson, Fraser MacBride), Saturday 20th to Sunday 21th of October 2007</li>\r\n    <li><a href=\"engel.php\">Go Figure -- Va Savoir</a> (Giovanni Tuzet, J&eacute;r&ocirc;me Dokic, Jo&euml;lle Proust), Thursday 13th December 2007 (Geneva)</li>\r\n    <li><a href=\"3rdmeeting.php\">third meeting</a>, 20th to 22th of December 2007</li>\r\n    <li><a href=\"4thmeeting.php\">fourth meeting</a>, Wednesday 5th to Friday 7th of March 2008</li>\r\n    <li><a href=\"5thmeeting.php\">fifth meeting</a>, Thursday 1st of May to Friday 2nd of May 2008</li>\r\n    <li><a href=\"6thmeeting.php\">Symposium on \"The Metaphysics of Knowledge\"</a> (Keith Hossack, Fraser MacBride, Mark Textor), Thursday 29th of May to Saturday 31st of May 2008</li>\r\n    <li><a href=\"7thmeeting.php\">seventh meeting</a>, Monday 18th August to Wednesday 20th August 2008</li>\r\n    <li><a href=\"8thmeeting.php\">eight meeting</a>, Thursday 4th September to Friday 5th September 2008</li>\r\n    <li><a href=\"relativism.php\">crash course on semantic relativism</a> (Isidora Stojanovic), Wednesday 12th to Thursday 13th November 2008</li>\r\n    <li><a href=\"11thmeeting.php\">workshop on Bradley's regress</a> (Arianna Betti, Richard Gaskin, Aleksandar Kellenberg, Anna-Sofia Maurin, Bo Meinertsen, Francesco Orilia, Benjamin Schnieder, Bill Vallicella, Jan Willem Wieland), Saturday 6th December to Sunday 7th December 2008</li>\r\n    <li><a href=\"15thmeeting.php\">workshop on definition and conjunction</a> (Cian Dorr, Fraser MacBride, Keith Hossack, Gonzalo Rodriguez-Pereyra), 30-31 May 2009</li>\r\n    <li><a href=\"17thmeeting.php\">Sinergia launch conference</a> (Stephan Leuenberger, Tobias Rosefeldt, Dean Zimmerman), 6-8 December 2009</li>\r\n    <li><a href=\"contingentism.php\">workshop on contingentism</a>, 24-26 September 2010 </li>\r\n    <li><a href=\"http://www.philosophie.ch/philipp/services/graduateschool11.phpl#grounding\">Grounding and determination</a> (Kelly Trogdon, Stephan Leuenberger, Jacek Brzozowski), 4-5 March 2011</li>\r\n    <li><a href=\"http://www.philosophie.ch/philipp/services/graduateschool11.php#truthmaking\">Truthmaking</a> (Raul Saucedo, David Liggins, Peter Schulte), 2-3 April 2011</li>\r\n    <li><a href=\"http://www.philosophie.ch/philipp/services/graduateschool11.php#properties\">Universals and Tropes</a> (Markku Kein&auml;nen, Herbert Hochberg, Peter Simons, Fraser MacBride), 22-23 April  2011</li>\r\n    <li><a href=\"http://www.philosophie.ch/philipp/services/graduateschool11.php#intrinsicextrinsic\">Properties, parts and values</a> (Kris McDaniel, Kathrin Koslicki, Wlodek Rabinowicz), 28-29 May 2011</li>\r\n    <li><a href=\"http://www.philosophie.ch/philipp/services/graduateschool11.phpl#exemplification\">Exemplification</a> (Mark Textor, Howard Peacock, Javier Cumpa), 10-11 June, 2011</li>\r\n    <li><a href=\"http://www.philosophie.ch/philipp/services/graduateschool11.php#essenceexemplification\">The Metaphysics and the Epistemology of Essence and Exemplification</a> (Sonia Roca-Royes, Nicholas B. Mantegani), 28-29 August 2011</li>\r\n    <li><a href=\"http://www.philosophie.ch/philipp/services/graduateschool12.php#1stworkshop\">Moore, Russell and those guys</a> (Herbert Hochberg, Fraser MacBride, James Levine), 28-29 April 2012</li>\r\n    <li><a href=\"http://www.philosophie.ch/philipp/services/graduateschool12.php#2ndworkshop\">Themes from Baxter</a> (Don Baxter, Alessandro Giordani, Jason Turner, Ingvar Johansson), 26-28 May 2012</li>\r\n    <li><a href=\"http://www.philosophie.ch/philipp/services/graduateschool12.php#3rdworkshop\">Truth</a> (Josh Parsons, Dan Zeman, Isidora Stojanovic, Sanna Hirvonen), 16-18 June 2012</li>\r\n    <li><a href=\"http://www.philosophie.ch/philipp/services/graduateschool12.php#4thworkshop\">What did we learn from two-dimensionalism?</a> (Manuel Garc&iacute;a-Carpintero, Gregory Bochner, Teresa Marques, Alfredo Tomasetta, Jens Kipper, Neil Mehta, Uriah Kriegel, Robert Michels), 6-8 July 2012</li>\r\n\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <br>\r\n\r\n  <h2>Geneva Summer School in the Philosophy of Physics</h2>\r\n  <p>I have organised the (hitherto) two installements of the Geneva Summer School in the Philosophy of Physics:\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><a href=\"gsspp08.shtml\">Geneva Summer School in the Philosophy of Physics 2008</a>, Monday 28th of July to Saturday 2nd of August 2008 (Arolla)</li>\r\n    <li><a href=\"gsspp09.shtml\">Geneva Summer School in the Philosophy of Physics 2009</a>, Sunday 5th of July to Saturday 11th of July 2009 (Arolla)</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n  <h2>graduate colloquia</h2>\r\n  <p>During my first 4 years in Geneva, I organised a series of weekly talks by international philosophers (a total of approx. 120 people):\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><a href=\"../docs/colloque06-programme.pdf\">summer term 06</a>\r\n    <li><a href=\"colloque05_06.php\">winter term 05/06</a>\r\n    <li><a href=\"colloque04.php\">summer term 04</a>\r\n    <li><a href=\"colloque03_04.php\">winter term 03/04</a>\r\n    <li><a href=\"colloque02_03.php\">winter term 02/03</a>\r\n    <li><a href=\"colloque02.php\">summer term 02</a>\r\n    <li><a href=\"colloque01_02.php\">winter term 01/02</a>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <br>\r\n\r\n  <h2>sequitur</h2>\r\n  <p>In December 2003, Norbert Anwander, Davor Bodrozic and Martino Mona and myself founded <a href=\"http://www.philosophie.ch/sequitur/\">sequitur</a>, the national association of philosophy graduate students.\r\n  <p>Since then, I've been involved in the organisation of:\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><a href=\"sequitur/1st.html\">1st conference June 22 2002</a>\r\n    <li><a href=\"sequitur/2nd.pdf\">2nd conference March 15 2003</a>\r\n    <li><a href=\"sequitur/3rd.html\">3rd conference October 18 2003</a>\r\n    <li><a href=\"sequitur/4th.pdf\">4th conference April 24 2004</a> (click <a href=\"sequitur/4th-CFP.pdf\">here</a> for the cfp)\r\n    <li><a href=\"sequitur/5th.pdf\">5th conference October 22-23 2004</a>  (click <a href=\"sequitur/5th-CFP.pdf\">here</a> for the cfp)\r\n    <li><a href=\"sequitur/6th.pdf\">6th conference April 8, 2005</a>\r\n    <li><a href=\"sequitur/7th.pdf\">7th conference October 29, 2005</a>\r\n    <li><a href=\"sequitur/8th.pdf\">8th conference, March 31th and April 1st, 2006</a> (click <a href=\"sequitur/8th-CFP.pdf\">here</a> for the cfp)\r\n    <li><a href=\"sequitur/9th-CFP.pdf\">9th conference, October 27 and 28, 2006</a>\r\n    <li><a href=\"sequitur/10th.shtml\">10th conference, June 21 and 22, 2007</a> (click <a href=\"sequitur/10th-CFP.pdf\">here</a> for the cfp)\r\n    <li><a href=\"sequitur/11th.shtml\">11th conference, January 14, 2008</a> (click <a href=\"sequitur/11th-CFP.pdf\">here</a> for the cfp)\r\n    <li><a href=\"6thmeeting.php\">12th conference, May 29, 30 and 31, 2009 (click <a href=\"../docs/program_6thmeeting.pdf\">here</a> for the programme)\r\n    <li><a href=\"sequitur/13th.shtml\">13th conference, September 25 and 26, 2009</a>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <br>", section: "workshops", url: "/workshops"},
  {title: "Services to the profession", text: "  <h2>dialectica</h2>\r\n  <p>Since 1999, I am managing editor of the Swiss philosophy journal <a href=\"http://dialectica.philosophie.ch/\">dialectica</a>, since 2004 published by Blackwell-Wiley. Founded in 1947 by Bachelard, Bernays and Gonseth, <b>dialectica</b> is now one of the best academic philosophy journals edited on the European Continent. Since 1999, I have been taking care of its day-to-day functioning, as well as the contact with authors and referees, and reading and evaluating (almost) every article. A year before <b>dialectica</b>'s long-time editor Henri Lauener died in 2002, I started collaborating with Gianfranco Soldati, appointed in 2000 to the University of Fribourg. Together, we managed to get <b>dialectica</b> published by Blackwell-Wiley and reduced the acceptance rate from over 20 % to 8 % (while the number of submissions tripled). Subsequently, I continued to work as managing editor and co-editor with Pascal Engel and then Marcel Weber: during this period, the number of submissions doubled again, now ranging from 250 to 300 per year, while we further reduced the acceptance rate to almost 8% and the median turnaround time to about 3 months. Dialectica is now ranked “A” in the European Research Index of the Humanities and the Australian Research Council’s ERA, is accessible to 5005 institutions worldwide and had about 38’264 full article downloads in 2017.\r\n    <br>\r\n    <br>\r\n\r\n  <h2>outreach</h2>\r\n  <p>I have undertaken two other initiatives to connect academic philosophy with the world outside the ivory tower:\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><a href=\"decouvrir.php\">D&eacute;couvrir la Philosophie</a> -- Portes Ouvertes au Laboratoire d'Exp&eacute;riences de Pens&eacute;e du D&eacute;partement de Philosophie de l'Universit&eacute; de Gen&egrave;ve, a highly successful serious of Saturday-afternoon introductions to some of the problems of our discipline;\r\n    <li><a href=\"http://www.philosophie.ch/philomaton-mobile/\">Le Philomaton Mobile</a>, a virtual laboratory, where anyone can ask questions or make comments, and philosophers answer or react.\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <br>\r\n\r\n\r\n  <h2>www.philosophie.ch</h2>\r\n  <p><a href=\"http://www.philosophie.ch\"><b>www.philosophie.ch</b></a>, the Swiss Portal for philosophy, is an outreach project I started in 2002. It aims at making available under one adress all information relevant to philosophy in Switzerland:\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li>to provide academics with a quick overview over colloquia, talks and other activities of Swiss philosophy departments;\r\n    <li>to offer to high-school students and other people interested in pursuing philosophy at university level up-to-date and authoritative information about their possibilities, the offers of the Swiss philosophy departments and their respective requirements;\r\n    <li>to further the contacts between philosophical academia and the broader public, by offering to people generally interested in philosophy high-quality information about philosophy as pursued academically.\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <p>The portal is widely used (more than 12’500 visits per month, excluding robots et al) and generously funded, both by the philosophy departments and private institutions, mostly by the Charles Hummer foundation, having now a annual turnaround of about 150’000 CHF. The internet portal <a href=\"http://www.philosophie.ch\"><b>www.philosophie.ch</b></a> is unique in its reach and professionality and has substantially contributed to the development of Swiss academic philosophy.\r\n    <br>\r\n    <br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n  <h2>ousia, the Centre for the Philosophy and Theology of Being at the University of Lucerne</h2>\r\n  <p>In Lucerne, I have founded <b>ousia</b>, an institutionally recognised umbrella for the research activities of the philosophers working in ancient, medieval philosophy and the philosophy of religion in Lucerne, the SNSF project \"Ontologie in der Schweiz\" and the Doctoral Programme of the same name. LINK TO THE WORKSHOPS PAGE\r\n    <br>\r\n    <br>\r\n\r\n  <h2>eidos, the Centre for Metaphysics at the University of Geneva</h2>\r\n  <p>In 2007, I founded <b>eidos</b>, the Centre for Metaphysics at the University of Geneva. Under the direction of Kevin Mulligan and Fabrice Correia, I've been its scientific coordinator for about 7 years.  I have also been coordinating one of its three founding research projects, the Swiss National Science Foundation  project \"Properties and Relations\" (the largest post-doc project ever funded in the humanities by the SNSF), and was involved in the Sinergia project \"Intentionality - the Mark of the Mental\", involving three PhD students and the Marie Curie Initial Training Network funded by the FP7 \"The Perspectivality of Thoughts and Facts\" including (in Geneva) one PhD student. I have worked in the SNF-sponsored project \"Fundamentality\".\r\n    <br>\r\n    <br>\r\n  <h2>Fundraising</h2>\r\n  <p>Over the years, I have been particularly active in fundraising, on the local, national and international level, raising a total of 3'088'387 CHF for the University of Geneva (much more, unfortunately, than my salary over this time!), 650'000 of which was conference money, particularly difficult to get. Not listed are the numerous research projects I have been involved with in my role as a \"research consultant\" at the University of Lausanne.\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li>SNF projects:\r\n      <ul>\r\n        <li>2009: Sinergia application \"Intentionality - the Mark of the Mental\" (with Olivier Massin and Graham Peebles) <b>accepted</b></li>\r\n        <li>2009: \"Fundamentality\", <b>accepted</b></li>\r\n        <li>2008: Sinergia application \"Time, Substance, Self. Reconciling common sense and contemporary science\" (with Olivier Massin and Michael Esfeld), <b>withdrawn</b></li>\r\n        <li>2007: SNF pro-doc application \"The (Meta-)Metaphysics of Properties and Relations\" (research module PDFM1-118626, 277840 CHF) (with Fabrice Correia), <b>accepted</b></li>\r\n        <li>2007: SNF project application \"Properties and Relations\" (100011-113688,  458854 CHF) (with Stephan Leuenberger, Christian W&uuml;thrich, Vincent Lam, Fabian Dorsch, Andri T&ouml;ndury), <b>accepted</b></li>\r\n      </ul>\r\n    <li>SNF summer schools\r\n      <ul>\r\n        <li>2013: SNF graduate school \"Lesser Entities\" (FNS 101112-147361, 25000 CHF), <b>accepted</b></li>\r\n        <li>2012: SNF graduate school \"The Metaphysics of Representation\" (FNS 101115-141421, 25000 CHF), <b>accepted</b></li>\r\n        <li>2011: SNF graduate school \"Fundamentality and Perspectivality\" (FNS 101111-135419, 25000 CHF), <b>accepted</b></li>\r\n        <li>2009: SNF graduate school \"The Metaphysics of Time\" (FNS 101111-125090, 25000 CHF, <b>accepted</b></li>\r\n        <li>2008: SNF graduate school \"Modalities: essence, necessity, and other adverbial modifiers\" (FNS 101111-120494, 25000 CHF),<b>accepted</b></li>\r\n        <li>2007: SNF graduate school \"Properties and Relations\" (FNS 101111-116566, 25000 CHF), <b>accepted</b></li>\r\n        <li>2006: SNF graduate school \"Mind and Metaphysics\" (FNS 101111-112120, 25000 CHF), <b>accepted</b></li>\r\n        <li>2004: SNF graduate school \"Abstract Entities\" (FNS 101111-103468 , 25000 CHF), <b>accepted</b></li>\r\n      </ul>\r\n    <li>European Science Foundation:\r\n      <ul>\r\n        <li>2012: Marie Curie Intra-European Fellowship (IEF) \"A World of Perspectives\", <b>rejected</b></li>\r\n        <li>2008: ERC starting independent researcher grant \"Time and Substance - Reconciling Common Sense and Contemporary Physics\" (with, and for, Fabrice Correia), <b>rejected</b></li>\r\n        <li>2008: Marie Curie Initial Training Networks (ITN) \"Perspectival Thoughts and Facts\" [Barcelona, St. Andrews, Geneva, Paris, London, Stockholm, Budapest], <b>accepted</b></li>\r\n        <li>2008: ESF network programme \"The Metaphysics of Properties\"  (with Olivier Massin, Akiko Frischhut),  <b>accepted</b></li>\r\n        <li>2008: ESF eurocores programme proposal \"The Values of Science\",, <b>rejected</b></li>\r\n        <li>2008: ERC advanced investigator grant \"The Metaphysics of Emotions\" (for Kevin Mulligan), <b>rejected</b>\r\n        <li>2007: ESF network programme \"The Metaphysics of Properties\", <b>rejected</b></li>\r\n        <li>2007: ESF eurocores programme proposal \"The Metaphysics in/of Science\", <b>rejected</b></li>\r\n        <li>2007: ERC starting independent researcher grant \"Essence and Modality\" (with Fabrice Correia), <b>rejected</b></li>\r\n        <li>2006: ESF network programme \"Properties and Make-Belief\"  (with Luc Schneider), <b>rejected</b></li>\r\n      </ul>\r\n    <li>Private foundations:\r\n      <ul>\r\n        <li>2012: Fondation Charles Hummel, for <a href=\"http://www.philosophie.ch\">www.philosophie.ch, (80'000 CHF), <b>accepted</b></li>\r\n        <li>2011: Fondation Charles Hummel, for <a href=\"http://www.philosophie.ch\">www.philosophie.ch, (30'000 CHF), <b>accepted</b></li>\r\n        <li>2008: Fondation Boninchi, \"Fundamentality\", <b>rejected</b></li>\r\n        <li>2008: Centro Stefano Franscini , \"Fundamentality\" (with Stephan Leuenberger), <b>rejected</b></li>\r\n      </ul>\r\n    <li>University:\r\n      <ul>\r\n        <li>2012: CRUS doctoral school (140000 CHF), <b>accepted</b></li>\r\n        <li>2007: e-learning project \"e-philosophie\", University of Geneva (72000 CHF) (<a href=\"../docs/elarning.pdf\">pdf</a>), <b>accepted</b></li>\r\n        <li>2005: Virtual Campus \"e-philosophy\", <b>rejected</b></li>\r\n      </ul>\r\n  </ul>", section: "services", url: "/services"},
  {title: "Research Interests", text: "  <p>I am working mostly in metaphysics, but have interests in the philosophies of logic, language and the mind, in epistemology, the philosophy of religion, the philosophy of perception and the philosophy of law.\r\n\r\n  <p>In case you are interested in my CV, <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"/getpdf/cv\">here it is</a>.\r\n\r\n  <p>At the moment, I am pursuing the following research projects, in no particular order (details and outputs below). Drafts are password-protected -- please ask me or guess (it's obvious...):\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><b>Fundamentally, there are no relations</b>. I argue that fundamentally/really/in fact, there are no relations. Aristotle, the medievals and Leibniz were right and Russell was wrong. There is structure, however, and\r\n    <li><b>Qua Qua Qua</b>. Qua objects, if only they could be made sense of, would be the real philosophers' paradise. Some proposals have been made, but the very rich treasury of historical antecedents has not yet been tapped into. This long.term project aims to develop, making full use of the history of philosophy, a systematic theory of qua objects (roles, aspects, cooky objects, accidental unities) and make a case for them by showing their theoretical usefulness across a wide range of traditional philosophical problems.\r\n    <li><b>How to Prove Your Existence in Three Simple Steps</b>. This grew out of my book on Descartes, a German-style rationalist reconstruction of the first three <i>Meditations</i> that itself grew out of my MA thesis. Over the years, it has put on some weight: it now includes (arguments for) controversial claims regarding the distinction between the analytic and the synthetic method\r\n      material falsity of ideas,\r\n    <li><b>An Ontology of Perspectives</b>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <br>\r\n  <br>\r\n\r\n  <h2 name=\"books\">Books</h2><a name=\"\">\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><b>Fundamentally, there are no relations</b>. Is relationality a fundamental feature of reality? Are relations reducible to monadic properties? I argue that these two questions are different, that the answer to both is \"no\", and that there is no tension between these two claims. Even though relational predications are indispensable, for both logical and metaphysical reasons, their truthmakers are structural, not relational facts. Relations – qualitative entities that have a direction and order their particulars – are not, and cannot be, fundamental. At the fundamental level of reality we do not find relations, but pure, irreducible and nonrelational structure. Russell’s famous arguments in the <i>Principles</i> do indeed rule out what he calls ‘monadism’ (the claim that every relational predication is equivalent to predications of only monadic predicates), but they fall short of refuting 'monism’: relational predications may be made true by monadic properties of wholes – and indeed are, if there are no fundamental relations. <br>\r\n      On the way to this conclusion, I examine different recent conceptions of relations, and argue that they all succumb to what I call the 'problem of converses'. The problem of converses arises from the fact that any account of relations according to which there are, or might be, non-symmetric relations, allows for what I call an ‘abstractionist’ definition of converse relations. Such converses then give rise to problems of ontological profligacy, metaphysical indeterminacy and infinite regress. Friends of relations have to accept that the facts of the cat being on the mat and of the mat being beneath the cat are different, that it is indeterminate which one is more fundamental and that the difference between the relations being on top of and being under cannot be spelled out in a non-circular way and has to be accepted as ‘brute’ – a package of claims which I take to be a reductio of the assumption that there are fundamental relations. <br>\r\n      Aristotle, the medievals, Leibniz and Spinoza were thus right, the modern orthodoxy is wrong: relations are not what explains how the world forms an inter-connected whole, but are on the contrary viewpoint-relative and perspectival abstractions from a prior structure. To many, such a conclusion will appear unbelievably ‘retro’: did not the Cambridge revolt against idealism rest on the case that modern logic showed the indis- pensability of relations? To assuage such worries, I take a closer look on the debate that is usually taken to have conclusively shown the need for relations: the famous exchange between Russell and the British Ideal- ists at the beginning of the last century. A proper understanding of the promise and the demise of Russell’s multiple relation theory of judgment, I argue, shows that Bradley was right: how relations relate can be understood only if they are seen as arising from, and being grounded in, metaphysically prior structure. It does not show that Russell was wrong, however: his theory can indeed be salvaged if couched in structuralist, not relational terms.\r\n    <li><b>How Things Are</b>, a very extensively expanded (and substantially revised) version of my thesis, in seven parts (of which (parts of) the first three comprised my thesis);\r\n      <ul>\r\n        <li>Determination -- a defense and generalisation of Fine's critique of modal accounts of essence, including an argument for non-modal and contingent concepts of essence and supervenience;\r\n        <li>A Theory of Truthmaking -- an analysis, and defense, of the core idea of truthmaker theory, including an argument against truthmaking necessitarianism;\r\n        <li>Properties and their Kind(s) -- a novel defense of the truthmaker argument in favour of properties, and an extension of it to a defense of Aristotelian universals, including an original account of determinables in terms of determination;\r\n        <li>Universals -- a novel account of intrinsicness used in an argument that, fundamentally, there are no relations, while tthere may well be intrinsic structure;\r\n        <li>Exemplification -- a defense of the view that exemplification is a relation, that it explains the unity we observe in the world and that properties are parts of the particulars that exemplify them;\r\n        <li>Generalised adverbialism -- a novel account of adverbial modification and its application to the problem of temporary intrinsics and the philosophy of modality;\r\n        <li>Qua qua qua -- a defense that so-called `qua objects' (`Picasso qua painter') are the referents of adverbially modified noun phrases, ontologically kosher and theoretically very useful.\r\n      </ul>\r\n    <li><b>Introduction &agrave; la logique</b> (375 pages), a comprehensive introductory logic course in French, to be used for a one-year first-year logic course;\r\n      <ul>\r\n        <li>This is the first (!!) comprehensive introduction to logic for philosophers written in French. It differs from Lepage's (1991) introduction and from the available translations of Quine (1971) by covering both natural deduction and tree methods, including correctness and completeness proofs for both propositional and predicate logic, and by paying particular (and non-partisan) attention to philosophical questions. It is ideally suited to be used in an (ambitious) logic course of four hours/semester, as they are being introduced (or, at least should be introduced) in francophone universities.\r\n      </ul>\r\n    <li><b>Ein Dritter Blick auf Descartes' Erste Philosophie</b> (518 pages), an interpretation and defense of the first three Meditations (an extensively expanded version of my MA thesis), in which I argue that\r\n      <ul>\r\n        <li>understanding the distinction between the so-called `analytic' and `synthetic' methods and Descartes' use of it allows us to understand how Descartes can reasonably claim that the doubt of <i>Med.</i> I is universal and the Cogito is indubitable; that universal doubt leaves reasoning intact; that universal doubt includes claims that are performatively indubitable; that it `follows' from our doubting it that we must hold it true that we think; and that the indubitability of our thinking is the `first' principle of Cartesian theism;\r\n        <li>a reconstruction of Descartes' three-step skeptical argument confirms his claim that the doubt so reached is the widest-ranging possible, encompassing in particular second-order knowledge claims that lie at the heart of the Cartesian validation of reason;\r\n        <li>that the Cartesian inference from thinking to existence (which I locate in the third, not the second <i>Meditation</i>) is valid and sound and substantiates Descartes' claim that we are essentially thinking beings.\r\n      </ul>\r\n    <li> (edited), <a href=\"http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/dltc.2009.63.issue-4/issuetoc\">The Philosophy of Vectors</a>, special issue of <b>dialectica</b>, 63(4), with Stephan Leuenberger, 2009 (under the name of \"Keller\").\r\n    <li> (edited), <a href=\"http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/dltc.2004.58.issue-3/issuetoc\">Formal Concepts</a>, special issue of <b>dialectica</b>, 58(3), with Fabrice Correia, 2004 (under the name of \"Keller\"). </li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <br>\r\n\r\n  <h2 name=\"papers\">Published Papers</h2>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li>Connectives, prenectives and dishonoured cheques of metaphysical explanation, in: Anne Reboul (editor), <a href=\"www.philosophie.ch/kevin/festschrift/\">Philosophical Papers Dedicated to Kevin Mulligan</a>, 2011. Book publication in: <i>Mind, Values, and Metaphysics. Philosophical Essays in Honor of Kevin Mulligan</i>, ed. Anne Reboul, volume 1. Cham: Springer Verlag, 2014.\r\n    <li>Racisme et b&ecirc;tise, in: Christine Tappolet, Fabrice Teroni, Anita Konzelmann Ziv (editors), Les Ombres de l'&Acirc;me. Penser les &eacute;motions n&eacute;egatives, Gen&egrave;ve: &Eacute;ditions Markus Haller, 2011, pp. 145-159. Italian translation: Razzismo e stupidit&agrave;'', in: <i>Le ombre dell’anima. Pensare le emozioni negative</i>, eds.~Christine Tappolet, Fabrice Teroni, Anita Konzelmann Ziv, Milano: Raffaello Cortina, pp. 81--93, 2013.\r\n    <li><a href=\"worldoftruthmakers.pdf\">A World of Truthmakers</a>, on Armstrong's new and old theories of truthmaking (presented at the truthmaker conference in Aix-en-Provence), in: Jean-Maurice Monnoyer (editor), Metaphysics and Truthmakers, Frankfurt a.M.: Ontos, pp. 105-156 (with a reply by David Armstrong). [click <a href=\"worldoftruthmakers_published.pdf\">here</a> for the book version]\r\n    <li><a href=\"armstrong_review.pdf\">David Armstrong, Truth and Truthmakers</a>, a review of Armstrong's latest book, arguing that he's mistaken about totality states of affairs, in Mind 118(472).\r\n    <li><a href=\"universals.pdf\">Universals</a>, a short presentation of the topic of universals, as it has been developped in Australasian philosophy, in in: A Companion to Philosophy in Australia and New Zealand, eds. Graham Oppy, Nick Trakakis, Melbourne: Monash ePress.\r\n    <li><a href=\"vectors.pdf\">The Philosophy of Vectors</a> (with Stephan Leuenberger), the introduction to the special issue of <i>dialectica</i>, discussing why vectorial properties are difficult to account for, in <a href=\"http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1746-8361.2009.01220.x/pdf\">dialectica 63(4)</a>, pp. 369-380.\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <br>\r\n\r\n  <!--<a name=\"draftpapers\"></a><h2>Draft papers</h2>\r\n  <p>Please click <a href=\"papers/index.php\">here</a> for the full text versions. Comments very welcome.\r\n  <br>\r\n  <br>\r\n  <h2>Research projects</h2>\r\n  <p>These are my current and future research projects - comments very welcome.\r\n  <ul>\r\n  <li><a href=\"papers/project.pdf\">A World of Perspectives. Representation without Mediation</a>, a long-term ambitious project for a monograph (and a couple of articles) on the metaphysics of representation.\r\n  <li><a href=\"papers/project1_adverbialism.pdf\">Adverbialism</a>, on the riddle of exemplification and the prospects of generalised adverbialism.\r\n  <li><a href=\"papers/project2_fundamentality.pdf\">Fundamentality</a>, attempting to reconcile science and common sense through a better understanding of the \"... is more fundamental than ...\" relation.\r\n  <li><a href=\"papers/project3_perspectivality.pdf\">Perspectival Facts</a>, trying to shed light on the perspectivality of thought and language by locating it in the outside world.\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <br>-->\r\n\r\n  <h2>Academic works</h2>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><a href=\"thesis.pdf\">my thesis</a> (2007)\r\n    <li><a href=\"memoire.pdf\">my \"m&eacute;moire de pr&eacute;doctorat\"</a> (2003)\r\n    <li><a href=\"info.pdf\">my master thesis in mathematics / theoretical computer science</a> (2003)\r\n    <li><a href=\"Descartes_liz.pdf\">my master thesis in philosophy</a> (2000)\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <br>\r\n\r\n  <h2>Law</h2>\r\n  <p>From 1998 to 2000, I have been studying law and working in the departement of penal law and criminology with Karl-Ludwig Kunz. Here is what I wrote at that time:\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li> A report on behalf of the Swiss Ministry of Justice on the jurisdiction on the Swiss law on help to victioms of crimes (with Karl-Ludwig Kunz): <a href=\"rechtsprechung.pdf\"> \"Die Rechtsprechung zum Opferhilfegesetz in den Jahren 1993-1998\"</a>.\r\n    <li> A report on behalf of the OECD on private bribery in Switzerland (with Nadja Capus and Karl-Ludwig Kunz): <a href=\"bribery.pdf\"> \"Private Bribery in Switzerland\"</a>.\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <br>\r\n\r\n  <a name=\"talks\"></a><h2>Talks</h2>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li>2015\r\n      <ul>\r\n        <li>Aspects - in Kant and in general, Doktorandenkolloquium des Lehrstuhls für Klassische Deutsche Philosophie, Berlin, 10th of December\r\n        <li>Processes and the Instant of Change, conference \"Limit Decision Problem -- Medieval and Contemporary Perspectives\", Excellence Cluster Topoi, Berlin, 20th of November.\r\n   